<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You are welcome to your opinion that it is false and irrelevant. I believe, based on a history of interaction that is indeed true and directly relevant. Since you've actually stated a position however, we'll skip this.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It is more than my opinion.  It is the truth.  If you think otherwise perhaps you would like to offer some justification besides [as stated above] the typically vacuous response, &quot;It is because it is&quot;.  You obviously think it is something that is relevant and needs to be hashed out, so get to it already.  Otherwise retract your baseless assertion.  To do otherwise is disingenuous.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>This is NOT stealing. Why would you consider it so? You purchased it, made a copy for your own use and destroyed the original. You still possess one copy of that intellectual property which you have purchased. Where's the theft in this?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, you misunderstand.  If I do not own a genuine copy, and did the above act, that would be stealing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You possess copyrighted material for which you have not paid. You have stolen intellectual property. Do you need a definition of intellectual property? ..or a link to copyright information and how they apply to intellectual property?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Are you arguing data is intellectual property?  If so I think Rigadoon makes a valid point.  Rigadoon said, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;If I trimmed the last 0 or 1 off of a file, so that it wasn't playable (not directly relevant for MP3s I know but hush) is it still &quot;their song?&quot;. Does the RIAA claim ownership to a random series of 0's and 1s regardless of what that series is or how it was produced? If I legally bought a song, ripped it, and wrote down all of those 0's and 1's that my particular ripper spat out and published them in a magazine, would I be infringing on the RIAA's copy protection?&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Further, do you believe that I am stealing intellectual property if I hear a song that, say, somebody is playing on their stereo in public on the beach?  Am I stealing intellectual property if I memorize the song and &quot;play&quot; it in my mind?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It depends on the use for those recordings, the methods with which they were obtained and the copyright information regarding the shows. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>This is what I am asking you</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for the sixth time now.  What conditions are necessary for the differentiation between stealing and not stealing in this instance?  Just the command of the law?<br>
<br>
If you cannot answer or do not have an answer I wish you would just say so instead of repeating yourself and dodging the question. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wolvar>Wolvar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>My third character is Lovawr</span><br>  Posts: 2373<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/10/03 7:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=865.topic&index=41>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RIAA files hundreds of cases against Music Swappers. </span><hr size=1> I've already explained why I feel your penchant for asking questions without stating a position is relevant, feel free to disagree.  I would hate to have to &quot;repeat myself&quot;.<br>
<br>
Destroying the original and making a copy results in a single physical copy of the intellectual property.  So the owner of the original copy could sue you for &quot;theft&quot; but the copyright owner should have no problem with this.<br>
<br>
<br>
Of course data is intellectual property, it's the primary reason FOR our intellectual property laws.  Rig's example is one way to defeat these laws, a loophole if you will.  However, modifying copyrighted information typically must be explicity allowed for in the licensing.  I doubt that the courts would agree that modifying a minor portion of the intellectual property would render a copyright null and void.  Unless you want to discuss reverse engineering?<br>
<br>
I think it's also quite obvious that copyright enfringement doesn't apply to &quot;playing things in your mind&quot;.  Try and be a little more silly would ya?<br>
<br>
As for conditions of stealing and not stealing, as I said, they are dependant upon the issues I stated.  The exact copyright licensing, the method of obtaining the copy and the use for the copy.  Copyright licensing varies quite widely and I don't see how to put it more explicit than that.  Perhaps you could suggest a scenario where something is considered illegal and you think it should be legal and that would be more productive.   <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=685611>KoT got me dis' stuff!</a> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 1540<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/10/03 7:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=865.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RIAA files hundreds of cases against Music Swappers. </span><hr size=1> Reverse engineering is an important part of this in general, especially regarding software, but doesn't really have anything to do with music, since half the bands out there don't even claim to be original anyway.  I cringe every time I hear a few measures from a Mozart sonata or something stitched into the middle of some hoarse rocker's song, but when you buy the CD, you're paying for the performance, not the music being played itself.  That's why people can sell performances of Mozart, which is otherwise public domain.<br>
<br>
I'm not a lawyer, so I can't comment on our copyright laws.  I do think that the RIAA has got itself stuck in a major rut, and is steaming full ahead to someplace it doesn't really want to go.  Time, and sales, will tell... <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A> at: 9/10/03 7:55 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hayzen>Hayzen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 724<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/10/03 8:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=865.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~digitalfoenix/shippou.jpg height=43 width=59></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RIAA files hundreds of cases against Music Swappers. </span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think it's also quite obvious that copyright enfringement doesn't apply to &quot;playing things in your mind&quot;. Try and be a little more silly would ya?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Why not?  What is the difference between memorizing a song and keeping it my mind and downloading a song and keeping it in my computer?  In both instances the song exists in the &quot;ether&quot;.  Is the location of the song the only thing that matters?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Of course data is intellectual property, it's the primary reason FOR our intellectual property laws<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, data is not the primary reason for intellectual property laws.  Intellectual property laws were created to protect <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>ideas</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> such as Mickey Mouse, or an original poem, or research results, etc.  This way if you create something like Mickey Mouse and somebody comes along and claims it as their own, or uses it in a public forum without giving you credit, or sells it for profit then you can sue them.  Intellectual property also used to pass relatively quickly into public domain.  Until the DMCA that is.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Unless you want to discuss reverse engineering?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Good question.  Say I go to a store and take down a technical schematic of an RCA television.  I then go home, with my schematic, and purchase parts from a wholesale dealer.  I assemble the parts, and now I have my own RCA type television.  Is that stealing?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Perhaps you could suggest a scenario where something is considered illegal and you think it should be legal and that would be more productive.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Are you reading the same post I am? We are talking about that very thing. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hayzen>Hayzen</A> at: 9/10/03 8:08 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wolvar>Wolvar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>My third character is Lovawr</span><br>  Posts: 2374<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/10/03 8:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=865.topic&index=44>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RIAA files hundreds of cases against Music Swappers. </span><hr size=1> Can you really not tell the difference between a memory and data on a PC?  They are nowhere near analogous.<br>
<br>
I guess we have no idea what the primary reason for intellectual property laws were but I would say that data is definitely the reason for the huge upsurgance of these disputes.  <br>
<br>
If you take a technical schematic of an existing copyrighted device, then you are not reverse engineering it.  You are stealing it.  Reverse engineering requires that your development be done in a vacuum with only conceptual ideas as the goal of your development work.  No technical details allowed.  Do you remember the huge Compaq/IBM lawsuit?<br>
<br>
My suggestion that you stick to scenarios where you feel something should be legal when it isn't was based on your disagreement with my response to your across-the-board question of what is and isn't legal.  It's a complicated subject and can't be cut-and-dried defined as you initially requested. <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=685611>KoT got me dis' stuff!</a> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 1541<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/10/03 8:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=865.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RIAA files hundreds of cases against Music Swappers. </span><hr size=1> &quot;Say I go to a store and take down a technical schematic of an RCA television. I then go home, with my schematic, and purchase parts from a wholesale dealer. I assemble the parts, and now I have my own RCA type television. Is that stealing?&quot;<br>
<br>
